<subSubSection id="8E1141247C07927309B24FEE2DAF2E22" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="110" pageId="16" pageNumber="109" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="51263E1D0176BA869D790A6E253FE266" pageId="16" pageNumber="109">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4C586A7703422FA7971091FBF688AC35" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="110" pageId="16" pageNumber="109">
<taxonomicName id="58EF63E428281B6D3119F36461D9FC55" authorityName="Hieron" authorityYear="1901" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella lechleri" order="Selaginellales" pageId="16" pageNumber="109" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="lechleri">
<emphasis id="C3A88293665E9F751401BD2B8FACB28E" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="109">Selaginella lechleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from Colombia and Peru (
<bibRefCitation id="D073B7B2EA28FC3D7AACD8B8AC4B10BE" author="Alston, AHG" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Botany" pageId="19" pageNumber="112" pagination="233 - 330" refId="B2" refString="Alston, AHG, Jermy, AC, Rankin, JM, 1981. The genus Selaginella in tropical South America. Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Botany 9: 233 - 330" title="The genus Selaginella in tropical South America." volume="9" year="1981">Alston et al. 1981</bibRefCitation>
). Additionally, 
<bibRefCitation id="6FE7FE75DBB3D34F353BFB6B80E33A3E" author="Smith, AR" journalOrPublisher="Pteridophytes, Spermatophytes: Acanthaceae-Araceae" pageId="21" pageNumber="114" pagination="296 - 314" refId="B25" refString="Smith, AR, 1995. Selaginellaceae. Pteridophytes, Spermatophytes: Acanthaceae-Araceae Vol. 2: 296 - 314" title="Selaginellaceae." volume="Vol. 2" year="1995">Smith (1995)</bibRefCitation>
cited it in Costa Rica, Panama, Venezuela, and Bo 
<pageBreakToken id="6814214AD29702568E5E629A29D041F6" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" start="start">livia</pageBreakToken>
, while 
<bibRefCitation id="2762CD50E637692CE35426653D962858" author="Cremers, G" editor="Funk, V" journalOrPublisher="Contributions from the United States National Herbarium" pageId="19" pageNumber="112" pagination="17 - 56" refId="B4" refString="Cremers, G, Hickey, RJ, Lellinger, DB, Mickel, JT, Moran, RC, Ollgaard, B, Smith, AR, 2007. Pteridophytes &amp; allies. In: Funk, V, Hollowell, T, Berry, P, Kelloff, C, Alexander, SN, Eds., Checklist of the plants of the Guiana Shield (Venezuela: Amazonas, Bolivar, Delta Amacuro; Guyana, Surinam, French Guiana). Contributions from the United States National Herbarium 55: 17 - 56" title="Pteridophytes &amp; allies." volume="55" volumeTitle="Checklist of the plants of the Guiana Shield (Venezuela: Amazonas, Bolivar, Delta Amacuro; Guyana, Surinam, French Guiana)." year="2007">Cremers et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="45C77C4A9ED1D2DA9C82687B478C3508" author="Mostacero, J" editor="Hokche, O" journalOrPublisher="Fundacion Instituto Botanico de Venezuela, Caracas" pageId="20" pageNumber="113" pagination="167 - 170" refId="B17" refString="Mostacero, J, 2008. Selaginellaceae. In: Hokche, O, Berry, PE, Huber, O, Eds., Nuevo catalogo de la flora vascular de Venezuela. Fundacion Instituto Botanico de Venezuela, Caracas: 167 - 170" title="Selaginellaceae." volumeTitle="Nuevo catalogo de la flora vascular de Venezuela." year="2008">Mostacero (2008)</bibRefCitation>
also cited it in Venezuela, and 
<bibRefCitation id="0C9486ED51008593F39DAF9757387792" author="Tropicos ®" journalOrPublisher="Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="21" pageNumber="114" publicationUrl="http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26615023" refId="B28" refString="Tropicos®, 2015a. Catalogue of vascular plants of Ecuador (W3CEC). Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden, http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26615023 [accessed 27.08.2015]" title="Catalogue of vascular plants of Ecuador (W 3 CEC). Tropicos. org" url="http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26615023" year="2015 a">Tropicos (2015a)</bibRefCitation>
registered it from Ecuador. I believe that specimens from Costa Rica and Panama are most likely 
<taxonomicName id="2715E0846968F5F87A97A894124A3A6A" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella anceps" order="Selaginellales" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="anceps">
<emphasis id="2EFD7A7EE3CE6D533E5CFC5185012983" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">Selaginella anceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(C. Presl) C. Presl, while those from Venezuela are best referred to another species. 
<taxonomicName id="D66466A3E3A600F39067933A2A8FECFD" authorityName="Hieron" authorityYear="1901" class="Lycopodiopsida" family="Selaginellaceae" genus="Selaginella" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Selaginella lechleri" order="Selaginellales" pageId="17" pageNumber="110" phylum="Lycopodiophyta" rank="species" species="lechleri">
<emphasis id="EE4FD772579C568C11DCC03F004F7A15" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="110">Selaginella lechleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is documented here to occur in the states of Acre and Amazonas, Brazil. It is characterized by its erect habit, lateral leaves with the basiscopic bases geniculate and usually glabrous, with the acroscopic margins short-ciliate along proximal ⅓ or dentate, otherwise sparsely denticulate to entire or serrate distally, and acuminate median leaves.
</paragraph>
